Initialization

We start the analysis by initializing the packages required in this section. We also define the root directory, within which all the input/output operations for this project will be performed. At the end of this document, a detailed software version information is provided for easier reproducibility of the analysis.

library(data.table)
library(gridExtra)
library(KEGGREST)
library(ggplot2)
library(reshape2)
path = "/Users/ashwin/Documents/Projects/YeastScreen/Essential_DAmP_screen/"

Slim gene ontology

Creating yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae) specific slim gene ontology based genesets. We create separate sets for molecular function and biological process. The data is obtained from Saccharomyces Genome Database (SGD). Keeping only those genesets having >= 5 and <= 500 genes.

dat = read.delim("https://downloads.yeastgenome.org/curation/literature/go_slim_mapping.tab", 
    header = F, stringsAsFactors = F)
colnames(dat) = c("ORF", "Gene", "SGDID", "GO_Aspect", "GOslim", "GOID", "Type")

bp = dat[dat$GO_Aspect == "P", ]
mf = dat[dat$GO_Aspect == "F", ]

createGoObj = function(godat) {
    godat = split(godat$Gene, godat$GOslim)
    godat = lapply(godat, function(x) {
        x = x[x != ""]
        x = unique(x)
        return(x)
    })
    
    return(godat)
}

bp = createGoObj(godat = bp)
cnt = sapply(bp, length)
bp = bp[cnt >= 5 & cnt <= 500]

mf = createGoObj(godat = mf)
cnt = sapply(mf, length)
mf = mf[cnt >= 5 & cnt <= 500]

KEGG pathways

Creating yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae) specific KEGG pathway based genesets. The data is obtained from Saccharomyces Genome Database (SGD). Keeping only those gene sets having >= 5 and <= 500 genes.

# metpath =
# read.delim(url('https://downloads.yeastgenome.org/curation/literature/biochemical_pathways.tab'),
# header = F, stringsAsFactors = F) colnames(metpath) = c('Pathway', 'Enzyme',
# 'ECnumber', 'Gene', 'Reference') metpath = metpath[- which(metpath$Gene ==
# ''),] metpath = split(metpath$Gene, metpath$Pathway) metpath =
# metpath[sapply(metpath, length) >= 3] yeastpath = metpath rm(metpath)

## Or KEEG pathways can be extracted from KEEG website directly

yeastpath = keggLink("pathway", "sce")
yeastpath = unique(yeastpath)

ind = seq(1, length(yeastpath), 10)
ind = data.frame(start = ind, end = c(c(ind[2:length(ind)] - 1), length(yeastpath)))

pathres = vector("list", length(yeastpath))

for (i in 1:nrow(ind)) {
    tmp = keggGet(yeastpath[ind[i, 1]:ind[i, 2]])
    pathres[ind[i, 1]:ind[i, 2]] = lapply(tmp, function(x) {
        x = grep(";", x$GENE, value = T)
        x = unique(sapply(strsplit(x, ";"), function(y) y[1]))
        return(x)
    })
    names(pathres)[ind[i, 1]:ind[i, 2]] = gsub(" - Saccharomyces cerevisiae (budding yeast)", 
        "", sapply(tmp, function(x) {
            x = x$NAME
        }), fixed = T)
    rm(tmp)
}
yeastpath = pathres
rm(i, ind, pathres)

# Keeping only the pathways with at least 5 genes
cnt = sapply(yeastpath, length)
yeastpath = yeastpath[cnt >= 5 & cnt <= 500]

Transcription fator targets

Creating yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae) specific transcription factor targets. The data is originally obtained from TF2DNA database. However, we use the data provided from YeastEnrichr which also based on TF2DNA but provides it in an easy-to-use format. Keeping only those gene sets having >= 5 and <= 1000 genes.

if (!file.exists(paste0(path, "publicData/TF2DNA_2018.txt"))) {
    download.file(url = "https://amp.pharm.mssm.edu/YeastEnrichr/geneSetLibrary?mode=text&libraryName=TF2DNA_2018", 
        destfile = paste0(path, "publicData/TF2DNA_2018.txt"))
}

tfs = readLines(paste0(path, "publicData/TF2DNA_2018.txt"))
tfs = lapply(as.list(tfs), function(x) {
    x = unique(unlist(strsplit(x, "\t", fixed = T)))
    x = x[!x == ""]
})
names(tfs) = sapply(tfs, function(x) x[1])
tfs = lapply(tfs, function(x) x[-1])

tfid = data.frame(study = names(tfs), tf = sapply(strsplit(names(tfs), "_"), function(x) x[1]), 
    stringsAsFactors = F)
tfid = split(tfid$study, tfid$tf)

tfs = lapply(tfid, function(x) {
    x = Reduce(intersect, tfs[x])
})

cnt = sapply(tfs, length)
tfs = tfs[cnt >= 5 & cnt <= 1000]

Yeast phenotypes

Creating yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae) specific gene phenotype information. The data is obtained from Saccharomyces Genome Database (SGD). Keeping only those gene sets having >= 5 and<= 1000 genes.

pheno = read.delim("https://downloads.yeastgenome.org/curation/literature/phenotype_data.tab", 
    header = F, stringsAsFactors = F)

pheno = pheno[, c(3, 6, 7, 10)]
colnames(pheno) = c("Gene", "Experiment", "MutantType", "Phenotype")

pheno = lapply(split(pheno$Gene, pheno$Phenotype), function(x) {
    x = x[x != ""]
    x = unique(x)
})
cnt = sapply(pheno, length)
pheno = pheno[cnt >= 5 & cnt <= 1000]

Integrated yeast genesets

Here we combine the KEGG and GO slim genesets into one meta yeast geneset object

genesets = list(KEGG = yeastpath, GOBP = bp, GOMF = mf, TFtargets = tfs, Phenotype = pheno)
saveRDS(genesets, file = paste0(path, "data/workspaces/YeastGeneSets.RDS"))

Geneset description

The number of pathways from each of the databases we used. ALL is simply the combination of the first 3.

tmp = lapply(genesets, length)
tmp = melt(tmp)

p = ggplot(tmp, aes(reorder(L1, value), value)) + theme_bw(base_size = 8) + labs(x = "Databases", 
    y = "Number of terms or genesets or pathways") + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + 
    geom_text(aes(label = value), vjust = -0.3, size = 3.5) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, 
    hjust = 0.5, vjust = 0.5))

ggsave(filename = paste0(path, "analysis/supplementary/Scerevisae_genesets.pdf"), 
    plot = p, width = 4, height = 4)

p

The size of each of the gene sets, i.e. the number of genes per gene sets. Not showing phenotypes as the list is too big to display.

tmp = lapply(genesets$GOMF, length)
tmp = melt(tmp)

p1 = ggplot(tmp, aes(reorder(L1, value), value)) + theme_bw(base_size = 9) + labs(x = "", 
    y = "Number of genes") + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + coord_flip() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

tmp = lapply(genesets$GOBP, length)
tmp = melt(tmp)

p2 = ggplot(tmp, aes(reorder(L1, value), value)) + theme_bw(base_size = 9) + labs(x = "", 
    y = "Number of genes") + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + coord_flip() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

tmp = lapply(genesets$KEGG, length)
tmp = melt(tmp)

p3 = ggplot(tmp, aes(reorder(L1, value), value)) + theme_bw(base_size = 9) + labs(x = "", 
    y = "Number of genes") + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + coord_flip() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

tmp = lapply(genesets$TFtargets, length)
tmp = melt(tmp)

p4 = ggplot(tmp, aes(reorder(L1, value), value)) + theme_bw(base_size = 8) + labs(x = "", 
    y = "Number of genes") + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + coord_flip() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

p = grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, p4, ncol = 2, nrow = 2)

ggsave(filename = paste0(path, "analysis/supplementary/Scerevisae_genesets_detailed.pdf"), 
    plot = p, width = 10, height = 20)
